    "finalTextLength": 1736,
    "finalText": "I don’t have that yet in the company knowledge base.\n\nI checked both:\n- Alleato’s internal **best-practice knowledge**\n- Broader **semantic knowledge** across stored content\n\nNothing came back that defines an official Alleato standard for owner-driven scope changes.\n\nWhat I can tell you instead is the right operating standard to adopt if you want one:\n\n- **Document the request immediately.** Treat every owner-driven change as a formal scope event, even if it starts as a casual comment in a meeting or email.\n- **Separate direction from authorization.** The owner can request pricing or feasibility review without authorizing the work. Those are not the same thing.\n- **Price and schedule it before proceeding whenever possible.** ROM first if speed matters, then a formal proposal with cost, time impact, assumptions, and exclusions.\n- **Track it in one place.** Each scope change should have an owner, status, cost exposure, schedule impact, and decision date.\n- **Get written approval.** Verbal approvals are where margin disappears and disputes start.\n- **Protect the base contract.** Make clear what is original scope vs added scope so teams do not absorb owner changes as “just part of the job.”\n- **Push field teams to flag scope drift early.** If supers, PMs, and subs start acting on direction before commercial alignment, you lose leverage fast.\n\nThe point of view: **best practice is not “be responsive to the owner.” It’s “be responsive without giving away scope, time, or margin.”**\n\nIf you want, I can turn this into one of two things right now:\n1. a **formal Alleato best-practice playbook** for owner-driven scope changes, or  \n2. a **knowledge base entry** so this becomes searchable company guidance going forward."
  },
